“Present Tense” is a real-time generative visual work built in p5.js. The piece produces abstract forms that continuously evolve based on three 
computational inputs: system time, randomized algorithmic variation, and live cursor movement. As the viewer moves their mouse, the density, speed, 
and direction of the forms shift. Because the system uses a time-based seed and live interaction, the exact configuration can never repeat.

The work is computational in both structure and execution. Every visual element is generated through code rather than pre-made images. 
The forms are calculated frame-by-frame using loops, conditionals, and probabilistic variation. The artwork does not exist as a fixed object but as 
executable instructions that unfold dynamically. Its visual state is the result of real-time computation responding to human input.

The piece speaks to what is authentically human by foregrounding presence and contingency. In The Work of Art in the Age of Mechanical Reproduction, 
Walter Benjamin argues that reproduction diminishes the “aura” of the artwork, its unique presence in time and space. In contrast, this work cannot be 
replayed as an identical event. Its form depends on a specific viewer’s gestures at a specific moment. The human does not control the system completely, 
nor does the system fully determine the outcome. Instead, the work emerges from their interaction.

Authenticity here is not located in a static object, but in an event. The viewer’s hesitation, speed, rhythm, and unpredictability shape the piece in 
ways that cannot be standardized or archived. The code can generate endlessly, but it requires embodied interaction to become meaningful. 
The work suggests that in a computational age defined by duplication, authenticity may persist in fleeting, unrepeatable encounters between human 
intention and algorithmic process.
